The Chronicle Business Correspondent THE Value Creation Challenge (VCC), a nationwide competition powered by Old Mutual Zimbabwe in partnership with the British Council held its 2021 Edition final pitch at the Eight2five Innovation Hub in Harare last Friday. Young people between 18 and 40 years from across the country pitched their ideas in categories that include: digital communication, young and funky, climate change, emerging technology, and data analytics culminating in five contestants at the final pitch. The programme forms part of Old Mutual Zimbabwe’s mission to make an impact in the communities they operate in. In this light, the group has also been innovative in finding ways to develop and support budding entrepreneurs. “At Old Mutual Zimbabwe, entrepreneurship is an important core pillar of our responsible business strategy. We are committed to supporting small businesses so that they realise their aspirations to grow. “The VCC continues its quest and has attained significant milestones to contribute to national development through employment creation opportunities in the communities we operate in,” said Lillian Mbayiwa marketing, public affairs and sustainability executive at Old Mutual. <img class="wp-image-591249 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/02/Old-Mutual-5.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/02/Old-Mutual-5.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/02/Old-Mutual-5-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> Msindazwe Ndhlovu- Noble Savage The final contestants were chosen during a two-day virtual pitch event held on the 29th and 30th of September 2021 and were awarded US$8,000.00 each in seed funding as they entered the accelerator programme for their businesses. The finalists include Eyellow Digital Network – Gary Ruwona (digital content creation), RAW Dried Fruit – Ruddy Makoni (young and funky), Mantis Coffee – Alfred Manyara (climate action), Nhanga Trust – Chipo Chikomo (climate action) and Msindazwe Ndhlovu – Noble Savage. These appeared before a panel of judges comprising: Lillian Mbayiwa, Linda Mariwande, a business development manager at Old Mutual Life Assurance Company, Davies Musoso, head of alternative investments at Old Mutual Investment Group, Roland Davies (country director British Council) and Farai Ncube (head of arts South Africa and cultural exchange SSA region British Council). The judges were given a board pack with details of each of the participant’s business and performance over the last three months ahead of the final pitch. The board pack was   used to ask questions and determine viability of the business. This board pack and a recommendation from Stimulus Africa, based on the business performance during the accelerator programme formed 50 percent weighting of the final score. The overall winner Noble Savage – Msindazwe Ndhlovu (climate action) received an additional US$10,000 to further capacitate his business. <img class="wp-image-591252 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/02/Old-Mutual-4.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/02/Old-Mutual-4.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/02/Old-Mutual-4-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> Lillian Mbayiwa -Marketing, Public Affairs & Sustainability Executive Old Mutual Msindazwe Ndhlovu- Noble Savage Sam Matsekete, group CEO at Old Mutual Zimbabwe said: “This challenge was designed out of an identified need for capacity building for entrepreneurs making a meaningful impact in their value chains. We believe in long-term value creation within our society to improve livelihoods sustainably into the future”. He added that participants have been presenting innovative and data-driven solutions that we believe will help address socio-economic issues and improve the society. “This journey starts with the transformation of how we do business and involves digital solutions, accessing expert skills, and leveraging other collaborative efforts in our communities,” he said. Noble Savage is a business that recycles waste plastic and glass to manufacture eco-friendly building materials which are lighter, stronger, durable and affordable. They make rooftiles, pavers, countertops and have prototyped a solar rooftile. The founder, Msindazwe Ndhlovu said: “I am really excited about winning and I still can’t believe it, but I want to say thank you to Old Mutual and British Council for programs such as these. VCC has really helped my business grow and thank you for asking me the hard questions about my business because as a result I am better prepared for the next growth phase of my endeavour.”    